import{_ as e,o as r,c as a,a as n,d as t,e as s,f as o}from"./app-631283dc.js";const i={},l=t("h1",{id:"_2022-年英语真题",tabindex:"-1"},[t("a",{class:"header-anchor",href:"#_2022-年英语真题","aria-hidden":"true"},"#"),s(" 2022 年英语真题")],-1),d=t("p",null,"2022年真题整理的单词+短语+长难句。",-1),m=o('<h2 id="text-1" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#text-1" aria-hidden="true">#</a> Text 1</h2><div style="text-align:justify;"><p>On a recent sunny day, 13,000 chickens <mark>roam</mark> over Larry Brown&#39;s 40 <mark>windswept</mark> <mark>acres</mark> in Shiner, Texas. Some rest in the shade of a parked car. Others drink water with the cows. This all seems random, but it&#39;s by design, part of what the $ 6.1 billion U.S. egg industry <mark>bets</mark> will be its next big thing: <mark>climate-friendly</mark> eggs.</p><p><span style="color:#f79646;"><b>在最近一个阳光明媚的日子里，在得克萨斯州夏纳小镇，1.3万只鸡<mark>漫步</mark>在拉里·布朗的40<mark>英亩</mark> <mark>迎风</mark>的土地上。一些鸡在一辆停放着的车的阴凉处休息。另一些鸡在和奶牛一起喝水。这一切看似都很随意,但却是有意为之,价值61亿美元的美国鸡蛋行业所<mark>押注</mark>=的部分内容将会是该行业的下一件大事:“<mark>气候友好型</mark>”鸡蛋。</b></span></p><p>These eggs, which are making their <mark>debut</mark> now on <mark>shelves</mark> for as much as $ 8 a dozen, are still <mark>labeled</mark> <mark>organic</mark> and animal-friendly, but they&#39;re also from birds that live on farms using <mark>regenerative</mark> <mark>agriculture</mark> - <strong>special techniques to <mark>cultivate</mark> rich <mark>soils</mark> that can <mark>trap</mark> greenhouse gases. Such eggs could be marketed as helping to fight climate change.</strong></p><p><span style="color:#f79646;"><b>这些鸡蛋正以8美元一打的高价<mark>首次在货架上亮相</mark>，它们仍然<mark>贴着</mark> <mark>有机</mark>和动物友好<mark>的标签</mark>，但此外，它们还产自生活在使用<mark>再生农业技术</mark>的农场里的禽类，再生农业技术即用于培养能够吸收温室气体的肥沃土壤的特殊技术。这种鸡蛋可以被宣传为有助于对抗气候变化。</b></span></p><p>&quot;I&#39;m excited about our progress,&quot; says Brown, who is adding more cover <mark>crops</mark> that <mark>draw</mark> <mark>worms</mark> and <mark>crickets</mark> for the chickens to eat. The birds&#39; waste then <mark>fertilizes fields</mark>. Such <mark>improvements</mark> &quot;allow our hens to forage for higher-quality natural feed that will be good for the land, the hens, and the eggs that we supply to our customers.&quot;</p><p><span style="color:#f79646;"><b>“我对我们的进展感到兴奋”，布朗说，他正在添加更多的<mark>覆盖作物</mark>，这些覆盖作物<mark>吸引</mark> <mark>蠕虫</mark>和<mark>蟋蟀</mark>供鸡食用。这些鸡的粪便随后成为<mark>田地的肥料</mark>。这样的<mark>改进</mark>“使我们的母鸡能够寻到更高质量的天然饲料,这些天然饲料将对土地、母鸡和我们供应给客户的鸡蛋都有利”。</b></span></p><p><strong>The egg industry&#39;s push is the first major test of whether animal products from <mark>regenerative</mark> farms can become the next <mark>premium</mark> offering.</strong> <mark>In barely</mark> more than a decade, <mark>organic</mark> eggs went from being <mark>dismissed</mark> as a <mark>niche</mark> product in natural foods stores to being sold at Walmart. More recently there were similar <mark>doubts</mark> about <mark>probiotics</mark> and plant-based meats, but both have exploded into major supermarket categories. If the sustainable-egg <mark>rollout</mark> is successful, it could <mark>open the floodgates</mark> for <mark>regenerative</mark> beef, <mark>broccoli</mark>, and <mark>beyond</mark>.</p><p><span style="color:#f79646;"><b>美国鸡蛋行业所做的努力是对再生农场生产的动物产品能否成为下一个优质产品的第一次重大测试。<mark>在仅仅</mark>十多年的时间里，<mark>有机</mark>鸡蛋从在天然食品商店里被视为小众产品而<mark>无人理睬</mark>，发展到了在沃尔玛出售。最近，人们也曾对<mark>益生菌</mark>和植物肉产生了类似的<mark>疑虑</mark>，但它们都已经突然爆发式地成了超市的主要(销售)品类。如果可持续鸡蛋的<mark>推出</mark>获得成功，它可能会为再<mark>生牛肉</mark>、<mark>西蓝花</mark>等<mark>更多</mark>产品<mark>打开闸门</mark>。</b></span></p><p>Regenerative products could be a hard sell, because the <mark>concept</mark> is <mark>tough to</mark> define quickly, says Julie Stanton, associate professor of agricultural economics at Pennsylvania State University Brandywine. Such farming also brings <mark>minimal</mark>, if any, <mark>improvement</mark> to the food products (though some producers say their eggs have more <mark>protein</mark>).</p><p><span style="color:#f79646;"><b>宾夕法尼亚州立大学布兰迪万河校区农业经济学副教授朱莉·斯坦顿说，再生产品可能很难销售,因为这个<mark>概念</mark> <mark>很难</mark>快速定义。这种农场生产方式如果对食品有<mark>改善</mark>的话，那也是<mark>微乎其微的</mark>(尽管一些生产商声称他们的鸡蛋含有更多的<mark>蛋白质</mark>)。</b></span></p><p>The industry is <mark>betting</mark> that the same consumers paying more for <mark>premium</mark> attributes such as <mark>free-range, non-GMO, and pasture-raised eggs</mark> will embrace <mark>sustainability</mark>. Surveys show that younger generations are more <mark>concerned about</mark> climate change, and some of the success of plant-based meat can be <mark>chalked up</mark> to shoppers wanting to signal their <mark>desire to</mark> protect the environment. Young adults &quot;really care about the <mark>planet</mark>,&quot; says John Brunnquell, president of Egg Innovations &quot;They are absolutely altering the <mark>food chain</mark> <mark>beyond</mark> what I think even they understand what they&#39;re doing&quot;.</p><p><span style="color:#f79646;"><b>美国鸡蛋行业期待,愿意为<mark>散养</mark>、<mark>非转基因</mark>和<mark>牧场饲养鸡蛋</mark>等优质特性支付更多<mark>费用</mark>的消费者们同样会接受<mark>可持续性</mark>这一特性。调查显示，年轻一代更加<mark>关心</mark>气候变化,而且植物肉的一些成功可以归因于想要表达自己对环境保护的<mark>渴望</mark>的购买者。年轻人“真的很关心<mark>地球</mark>”，Egg Innovations公司的总裁约翰·布伦奎尔说,“他们毫无疑问正在改变<mark>食物链</mark>，这<mark>超出</mark>了我的想象，甚至超出这些年轻人对自己正在做的事情的理解”。</b></span></p></div><h3 id="text1-单词表" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#text1-单词表" aria-hidden="true">#</a> text1 单词表</h3><table><thead><tr><th style="text-align:center;">单词</th><th style="text-align:center;">释义</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>roamn</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.漫游；v.徜徉；漫步；闲逛；摸遍</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>windswept</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">adj. 受大风吹的；当风的；似被风吹散的；乱蓬蓬的</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>acres</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.英亩；土地；〈口〉大量</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>bets</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.赌注；打赌；〈口〉意见；适于做某事的人；v.打赌；下赌注；敢断定；用…打赌</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>climate-friendly</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">气候友善；气候友善性；气候友好型的</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>debut</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">v.初次登台；n.处女秀；adj.首张的</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>shelves</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n. “shelf”的复数；v.“shelve”的第三人称单数；书架；架子；货架</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>labeled</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n. 标签；标记；签条；（不恰当的）称谓；标签；标记；绰号；(字典中用的)说明性略语；v.贴标签于；把…列为；(用放射性同位素)使(元素或原子)示踪；贴标签于；尤指不公正地）把…称为</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>organic</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">adj.有机的；不使用化肥的；绿色的；有机物的；n.分子有机体</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>regenerative</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">adj.再生的；使更生的；更新的；使悔悟的</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>agriculture</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n. 农业；农学；农艺</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>cultivate</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">v.培育；栽培；耕作；种植</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>soils</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.土壤；土地；土质；滋生地；v.弄脏；污染；污辱；给…上粪[施肥]</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>trap</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.（捕捉动物的）陷阱；圈套；诡计；牢笼；v.使落入险境；使陷入困境；卡住；夹住</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>crops</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.作物；庄稼；产量；嗉囊；v.剪裁；剪短；啃吃（青草或其他植物上面的部分）；有收成</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>draw</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.抽彩；抽奖；抽签；平局；v.描画；拖（动）；拉（动）；牵引；吸引；获得</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>worms</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.蠕虫；蜗杆；【机】螺线；(蒸馏器的)螺旋管；v.虫一般地爬；使(虫一般)慢慢向前；慢慢地爬过</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>cricket</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.【虫】蟋蟀；【体】板球；矮木凳；垫脚凳；adj.公平的；v.【体】打板球</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>fertilize</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">v.使肥沃；【生】使受孕[受精]；施肥</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>fields</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.田野；田地；油田；原野；v.(棒球,板球运动中)接<a href="%E7%90%83">截</a>；使(球队或球员)入场；adj.野生的；野外的；实地的</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>improvement</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n. 改进；进步；</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>premium</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.保险费；额外费用；奖金；津贴；adj.优质的；昂贵的；价格更高的</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>in barely</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">在短短</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>dismissed</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">v.解雇；打发走；开除(学生等)；放弃(企图等)</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>niche</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.壁龛；舒适或称心的工作（或生活等）；（产品的）商机；市场定位</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>doubts</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.怀疑；疑惑；疑惧；v.怀疑；不信；恐怕；不信 (about of)</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>probiotics</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.【微】益生菌</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>rollout</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n. 首次展示；上线；滑跑；试运行</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>open the floodgates</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">打开了闸门；发泄</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>broccoli</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.花椰菜；青花菜；绿花椰菜【植】西兰花</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>beyond</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">prep.超出；在（或向）…较远的一边；晚于；迟于；n.那边；adv.以远；在另一边；在（或向）更远处</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>concept</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n. 概念；观念；设想；观点</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>tough to</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">很难去做某事</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>minimal</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">adj.极小的；极少的；最小的；n.最简单派艺术作品</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>protein</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.蛋白质</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>betting</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.打赌；赌钱</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>sustainability</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.可持续性；永续性；可持续发展</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>chalked about</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">刷新纪录</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>planet</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.行星；地球（尤指环境）；</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>food chain</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">食物链</td></tr></tbody></table><h2 id="text-2" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#text-2" aria-hidden="true">#</a> Text 2</h2><div style="text-align:justify;"><p>More Americans are <mark>opting</mark> to work well into retirement, a growing trend that <mark>threatens</mark> to <mark>upend</mark> the old <mark>workforce model</mark>.</p><p><span style="color:#f79646;"><b>更多的美国人<mark>选择</mark>在退休后继续工作，这一日益增长的趋势可能会<mark>颠覆</mark>旧的<mark>劳动力模式</mark>。</b></span></p><p>One in three Americans who are at least 40 have or plan to have a job in retirement to prepare for a longer life, according to a survey conducted by Harris Poll for TD Ameritrade. Even more surprising is that more than half of “unretirees”- those who plan to work in retirement or went back to work after retiring- said they would be employed in their later years even if they had enough money to settle down, the survey showed.</p><p><span style="color:#f79646;"><b>哈里斯民意调查机构为TD Ameritrade（亚美利交易控股公司）开展的一项调查显示，在40岁及以上的美国人中，有三分之一的人已经或计划在退休后继续工作，为更长远的人生做准备。更令人惊讶的是，该调查显示，超过一半的“不退休者”——那些计划退休后继续工作或退休后重返工作岗位的人—-表示即使已经有足够的钱过安定的生活，他们也会在晚年继续就业。</b></span></p><p>Financial needs aren&#39;t the only <mark>culprit</mark> for the “unretirement“ trend. Other reasons, according to the study, include personal <mark>fulfillment</mark> such as staying mentally fit, <mark>preventing</mark> <mark>boredom</mark> or avoiding <mark>depression</mark>. About 72% of “unretiree“ respondents said that they would return to work once retired to keep mentally <mark>fit</mark> while 59% said it would be tied to making ends meet.</p><p><span style="color:#f79646;"><b>经济需求并不是形成“不退休”趋势的唯一原因。这项研究显示，其他原因还包括个人<mark>满足</mark>，例如保持精神<mark>健康</mark>、防止<mark>无聊</mark>或避免<mark>抑郁</mark>。</b></span></p><p>“The concept of retirement is <mark>evolving</mark>,”said Christine Russell, senior manager of retirement at TD Ameritrade. “It&#39;s not just about finances. The value of work is also driving folks to continue working past retirement.”</p><p><span style="color:#f79646;"><b>“退休的概念正在<mark>演变</mark>”，TD Ameritrade退休部门高级经理克里斯蒂娜·拉塞尔表示。“这不仅关乎财务状况。工作的价值也促使人们在退休后继续工作”。</b></span></p><p>One reason for the change in retirement patterns: Americans are living longer. The share of the population 65 and older was 16% in 2018, up 32% from the prior year,according to the US. Census Bureau. That&#39;s also up 302% since 2010. Older Americans are also the fastest-growing <mark>segment</mark> of the US. workforce, and <mark>boomers</mark> are expected to live longer than previous generations. The percentage of retirement-age people in the labor force has doubled over the past three decades. About 20% of people 65 and older were in the workforce in February, up from an all-time low of 10% in January 1985, according to money manager United Income.</p><p><span style="color:#f79646;"><b>退休模式发生变化的一个原因是:美国人的寿命延长了。在美国，老年人也是劳动力中增长最快的群体。在过去30年里，退休年龄人口在劳动力中的比例翻了一番。根据资金管理公司United Income的数据，2019年2月，约有20%的65岁及以上人口参加工作，该数据高于1985年1月的10%这一一历史最低点。</b></span></p><p>Because of longer life spans, Americans are also <mark>boosting</mark> their savings to <mark>preserve</mark> their <mark>nest eggs</mark>, the TD Ameritrade study showed, which surveyed 2000 adults between 40 to 79. Six in 10 &quot;unretirees“ are increasing their savings in anticipation of a longer life, according to the survey. Among the most popular ways they are doing this, the company said, is by reducing their overall expenses, securing life insurance or maximizing their contributions to retirement accounts.</p><p><span style="color:#f79646;"><b>TD Ameritrade调查了2000名40岁到79岁的成年人，研究结果显示，由于寿命延长，美国人也在<mark>增加</mark><mark>积蓄</mark>=以保存自己的储备金。因为预计寿命会延长，60%的“不退休者”正在增加他们的积蓄。该公司表示，这些“不退休者”增加积蓄最普遍的方式之一是减少总开支、购买人寿保险或最大限度地增加退休账户供款。</b></span></p><p>Unfortunately, many people who are <mark>opting</mark> to work in retirement are preparing to do so because they are worried about making ends meet in their later years, said Brent Weiss,a <mark>co-founder</mark> at Baltimore-based financial-planning firm Facet Wealth. He suggested that preretirees should speak with a financial adviser to set long-tenn financial goals.</p><p><span style="color:#f79646;"><b>总部位于巴尔的摩的财务规划公司Facet Wealth的联合创始人布伦特.韦斯说，不幸的是，许多<mark>选择</mark>退休后继续工作的人正准备这样做，因为他们担心晚年的<mark>收支平衡问题</mark>。他建议，即将退休的人应该与财务顾问谈谈，以制定长期的财务目标。</b></span></p><p>“The most challenging moments in life are getting married, starting a family and ultimately retiring”, Weiss said. “It&#39;s not just a financial decision, but an emotional one. Many people believe they can&#39;t retire”</p><p><span style="color:#f79646;"><b>“人生中最具挑战性的时刻是结婚、组建家庭和最终退休”，韦斯说。“这不仅是一个财务决策，也是一个情感决策。很多人认为自己不能退休”。</b></span></p></div><h3 id="text2-单词表" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#text2-单词表" aria-hidden="true">#</a> text2 单词表</h3><table><thead><tr><th style="text-align:center;">单词</th><th style="text-align:center;">释义</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>opting</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">v.选择</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>threatens</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">v.威胁；预示凶兆；像要发生；快要来临</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>upend</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">v.翻倒；倒放；使颠倒</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>culprit</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.罪犯；肇事者；犯错的人；引起问题的事物</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>fulfillment</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.实现；履行；完成；满足</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>preventing</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">v.预防；阻止；妨碍；制止</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>boredom</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.无聊；厌倦；厌烦</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>depression</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.抑郁</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>fit</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">adj.健壮的；健康的；（质量、素质或技能）适合的；n. （癫痫等的）突发；昏厥；痉挛；一阵（忍不住的咳嗽、笑）；v.合身；（大小、式样、数量适合）可容纳；试穿（衣服）；安置；adv. 适合地；适时地</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>evolving</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">v.进化；发展；发出(热等)；使进化</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>segment</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">n.段；部分；片；弓形；v.分割；划分</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>boomers</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">战后婴儿；战后婴儿潮时期；潮</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>boosting</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">v.提高；促进；增加；刺激；n.提高；促进；推动；升</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>preserve</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">v.保留；保护；保存；维护；n.（某人或群体活动、工作等的）专门领域；果酱；腌菜；泡菜</td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:center;"><strong>nest eggs</strong></td><td style="text-align:center;">积蓄</td></tr></tbody></table>',8);function g(c,k){return r(),a("div",null,[l,d,n(" more "),m])}const y=e(i,[["render",g],["__file","2022年真题.html.vue"]]);export{y as default};
